1. Initialize Provider
terraform init

2. Format Terraform Files (optional but recommended)
terraform fmt

3. Validate Configuration
terraform validate

4. Show Execution Plan
terraform plan

5. Apply Configuration (create VM)
terraform apply -auto-approve

6. Show Output Values
terraform output

7. Show Current State (optional)
terraform show

8. Destroy VM
terraform destroy -auto-approve

VirtualBox Commands (if needed)
Check Host-Only Networks
VBoxManage list hostonlyifs

Check All VMs in VirtualBox
VBoxManage list vms

Check Running VMs
VBoxManage list runningvms

Manually Start VM (optional)
VBoxManage startvm "<vm-name>" --type headless

Manually Stop VM (optional)
VBoxManage controlvm "<vm-name>" poweroff



Windows PowerShell Commands
Check PATH for VirtualBox
echo $env:PATH

Confirm VirtualBox installed
vboxmanage --version

‚úÖ Create VirtualBox Host-Only Adapter (Windows)
Step-1 ‚Äî Create the adapter
VBoxManage hostonlyif create


This will output something like:

Interface 'VirtualBox Host-Only Ethernet Adapter' was successfully created

Step-2 ‚Äî Configure IP for the adapter
VBoxManage hostonlyif ipconfig "VirtualBox Host-Only Ethernet Adapter" --ip 192.168.56.1 --netmask 255.255.255.0

**Step-3 ‚Äî Enable DHCP (optional)
VBoxManage dhcpserver add --ifname "VirtualBox Host-Only Ethernet Adapter" --ip 192.168.56.100 --netmask 255.255.255.0 --lowerip 192.168.56.101 --upperip 192.168.56.254 --enable


If DHCP already exists, update it:

VBoxManage dhcpserver modify --ifname "VirtualBox Host-Only Ethernet Adapter" --enable

üîç Verify host-only interfaces
VBoxManage list hostonlyifs


You should see:

Name:            VirtualBox Host-Only Ethernet Adapter
IPAddress:       192.168.56.1
NetworkMask:     255.255.255.0

